---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Hero from '../components/Hero.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Jordan Hornblow | Software Engineer">
  <Hero />
  <main class="mx-auto max-w-2xl px-6">
    <!-- Who am I? -->
    <section class="py-5">
      <h2 class="mb-6 text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight md:text-3xl">Who am I?</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-brand-text">
        <p>
          Hi, I'm Jordan. I turn code into systems by day and get lost in music by night.
          I was born in New Zealand, where I spent the first 23 years of my life. After living
          through thousands of earthquakes in Christchurch, I decided a broken city wasn't for
          me at the time and moved to Melbourne, Australia in 2014. Eight years later, in mid-2022,
          I relocated to Austin, Texas for work.
        </p>
        <p>
          I returned to Te Waipounamu, Aotearoa in early 2024 for health reasons and worked
          remotely from home.
          I'm still here but will be back in Melbourne for the next chapter very soon. Coming home was energizing, the warmth and
          strength of Kiwi culture reminded me how greedy and transactional much of the world
          had become in my decade away.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- What do I do? -->
    <section class="py-5">
      <h2 class="mb-6 text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight md:text-3xl">What do I do?</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-brand-text">
        <p>
          I see product development like music. Every layer of the stack is an instrument: you
          can play them on their own, but when you understand how they fit together, that's when
          you create something that really sings. Going deep into the full stack lets me architect
          systems that are stronger, more resilient, and easier to tune when things go off-key.
        </p>
        <p>
          I thrive on the creative rush of building from the ground up. But I've also learned to
          appreciate working with existing systems: maintaining, refining, and
          pushing them to perform better. Whether it's writing code, squashing bugs,
          or shaping the bigger picture, I approach it like composing: build, listen, adjust,
          iterate until it feels right.
        </p>
        <p>
          My current stack includes AWS, Terraform, Node.js/Nest.js, TypeScript,
          React, GraphQL, and Python. I've been experimenting with AI-assisted
          development workflows, modern cloud infrastructure, and building smaller systems
          quickly from first principles.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Systems I Build -->
    <section class="py-5">
      <h2 class="mb-6 text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight md:text-3xl">Systems I build</h2>
      <div class="space-y-6 text-base leading-relaxed text-brand-text">
        <div>
          <h3 class="mb-1 font-semibold text-brand-accent">Scalable SaaS platforms</h3>
          <p>Designing and evolving systems that handle real-world complexity: multi-tenant architectures, integrations, and large operational workflows.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="mb-1 font-semibold text-brand-accent">Automation and developer infrastructure</h3>
          <p>Building tooling, pipelines, and infrastructure that reduce manual work and improve engineering velocity.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="mb-1 font-semibold text-brand-accent">AI-assisted systems</h3>
          <p>Applying AI and automation to practical problems: document processing, workflow automation, and intelligent pipelines.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="mb-1 font-semibold text-brand-accent">Integration platforms</h3>
          <p>Designing APIs and integration layers that allow systems to communicate reliably across organisations.</p>
        </div>
        <p class="pt-2">
          <a href="https://603.nz" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 font-semibold text-brand-accent hover:underline">
            Explore engineering projects
            <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="h-4 w-4" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M14 5l7 7m0 0l-7 7m7-7H3" />
            </svg>
          </a>
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- What does jch254 mean? -->
    <section class="py-5">
      <h2 class="mb-6 text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight md:text-3xl">What does jch254 mean?</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-brand-text">
        <p>
          jch254 was my University of Canterbury login username. I've been using it as my handle
          across GitHub, domains, and everywhere else since 2009. At this point it's less of a
          username and more of an identity.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Anything else? -->
    <section class="pt-5 pb-10">
      <h2 class="mb-6 text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight md:text-3xl">Anything else?</h2>
      <div class="space-y-4 text-base leading-relaxed text-brand-text">
        <p>
          Music is life. I'm a musician, producer, and long-time vinyl collector. During the
          Melbourne COVID lockdowns I leaned hard into that passion, amassing over 800 records,
          which I catalog and track through Discogs (OS beta tester represent). Music
          isn't just a hobby, it's a way of making sense of the world: listening, creating, and
          always chasing the next sound that moves me.
        </p>
        <p>
          I'm also an active contributor to open-source software. Beyond code, I enjoy stepping behind the camera to
          capture moments. I keep a blog, project portfolio, and GitHub profile where I share
          what I'm building.
        </p>
        <p>
          Most importantly, I'm an advocate for suicide awareness and prevention, a cause deeply
          personal after losing an uncle and two close friends. It's a reminder that behind the
          code, the projects, and the music, people and connection matter most.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>
